    <p>Mr. RUSELL ROBERTS (University Economist, George Mason University): Have you ever been to Huntsville, Alabama?  </p>
    <p>SIEGEL: Yes. </p>
    <p>Mr. ROBERTS: Yeah, my parents live there now. There's a highway. It's about 12 or 14 lanes. Its stretches that way for about three miles, then it shrinks down to a sort of a civilized six. Why? Why is there this remarkable lake of asphalt? There is no traffic generating the need for a 14-lane highway or 12, whatever. It is just unbelievably wide. I assume some senator in Alabama that was politically powerful got that passed.  </p>
    <p>SIEGEL: Well, we heard from some indignant listeners in Huntsville. There was this from Dan Price. Imagine that: roads designed to handle the traffic flow. Enjoy your drive home on the Beltway, professor. My commute is now only 15 minutes. That was cruel. Well, we're joined now by the mayor of Huntsville, Tommy Battle. Mayor Battle, is there a 14- or 12-lane lake of asphalt in Huntsville, Alabama?  </p>
    <p>Mayor TOMMY BATTLE (Huntsville, Alabama): No, there isn't. We have about 105,000 cars a day traveling on that roadway, so it's a necessary part of Huntsville, and it's also one of our economic drivers.  </p>
